<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">XIV</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suis=
se Group AG used to have a product called XIV, the VelocityShares Daily Inv=
erse VIX Short-Term ETN, an exchange-traded note that you could buy to bet =
against volatility. Loosely speaking, XIV gave you the daily inverse of VIX=
, the CBOE Volatility Index: If the VIX went up by 5% in a day, you lost 5%=
 of your money; if it went down by 10% in a day, you added 10% to your mone=
y. One day =E2=80=94=C2=A0Monday, Feb. 5, 2018 =E2=80=94=C2=A0the VIX went =
up by 115.6%, from 17.3 the previous Friday to 37.3 that day.[1] So XIV inv=
estors lost all their money that day, and XIV doesn=E2=80=99t exist anymore=
. Fine!?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that was an oversimplifi=
ed description of how XIV works. Actually it tracked, not the actual VIX, b=
ut changes in=C2=A0an index of near-term=C2=A0<em>futures contracts=C2=A0</=
em>on the VIX. The reason for this is that Credit Suisse, the issuer of the=
 exchange-traded note, had to hedge its exposure: If VIX went down, Credit =
Suisse owed XIV holders more money. It could hedge that risk by being short=
 VIX futures: If VIX went down, it would make more money on the futures. Be=
cause futures expire, it had to roll those futures over =E2=80=94=C2=A0shor=
t some next-month futures and then, as their expiration approaches, close s=
ome of them out and short some following-month futures=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0=
and there is an index that=C2=A0mechanically tracks that strategy, basicall=
y a weighted=C2=A0average of the prices of the next couple of months of VIX=
 futures, with the weighting changing as one future gets closer to expirati=
on. The index is called the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/23882452.285958/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3BnbG9iYWwuY29tL3NwZGppL2VuL2luZ=
GljZXMvc3RyYXRlZ3kvc3AtNTAwLXZpeC1zaG9ydC10ZXJtLWluZGV4LW1jYXAvI292ZXJ2aWV3=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2ab3e6c6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">S&amp;P 500 VIX Short-Term Futures Index ER</a>; =
you can read how it=E2=80=99s calculated <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/23882452.285958/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3BnbG9iYWwuY29tL3Nw=
ZGppL2VuL2RvY3VtZW50cy9tZXRob2RvbG9naWVzL21ldGhvZG9sb2d5LXNwLXZpeC1mdXR1cmV=
zLWluZGljZXMucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB65db8631" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">here</a>.=C2=A0S&amp;P Dow Jones=
 Indices LLC, the index provider, looks at the prices of VIX futures, plugs=
 them into a formula, and calculates the level of the index from the future=
s prices.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On that Monday, Feb. 5, 2018, whe=
n VIX more than doubled, the VIX futures index did not=C2=A0<em>quite=C2=A0=
</em>double; XIV investors lost, not 100% of their money (or 115%), but abo=
ut 95%. The XIV notes had a provision that, if they lost more than 80% of t=
heir value in one day, Credit Suisse could redeem them, and it did. It paid=
 investors $5.99 per note; the XIV notes had closed at $115.55 on Friday, F=
eb. 2, 2018, the trading day before it blew up.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Investors in XIV were not happy about losing (almost) all their money.=
 One reason they were not happy about it has to do with Credit Suisse=E2=80=
=99s hedging of the XIV notes. To hedge the notes, Credit Suisse had to sho=
rt VIX futures, and it had to rebalance its hedge each day as the VIX futur=
es index=C2=A0went up and down. When the index went=C2=A0<em>up</em>, Credi=
t Suisse had to=C2=A0<em>buy back=C2=A0</em>some of the futures it had shor=
ted. This caused the futures index to go up more, which caused it to buy ba=
ck more futures, etc. On Feb. 5, 2018, when the VIX went up a lot, (1) Cred=
it Suisse apparently bought a whole bunch of futures, (2) this drove the VI=
X futures index up even more, (3) one result was that Credit Suisse=E2=80=
=99s customers, the owners of XIV notes, lost all their money, and (4) anot=
her result=C2=A0is probably that Credit Suisse=C2=A0<em>made=C2=A0</em>a lo=
t of money.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The customers sued, claiming=
 that Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s hedging activity =E2=80=94=C2=A0which is the =
standard way to hedge this product, and was fully disclosed, but which does=
 look kinda bad in hindsight! =E2=80=94=C2=A0was actually market manipulati=
on. A court tossed out their case, but last month an appellate court brough=
t it back, concluding that the customers could try to persuade a jury that =
Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s hedging was market manipulation. We <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23882452.285958/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMDQvdW5kZXItYXJtb3VyLWVh=
cm5pbmdzLXdlcmUtYS1iaXQtbWlzbGVhZGluZw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa80e4a44" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked abo=
ut the decision</a>=C2=A0a couple of weeks ago.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">There was, however, another reason that the XIV investors weren=E2=80=
=99t happy. Some of them bought XIV notes during the day on Feb. 5, 2018. I=
n particular, some of them bought XIV notes after 4 p.m. that day, when the=
 value of the XIV notes had already collapsed. But they didn=E2=80=99t know=
 that yet, because Credit Suisse was reporting incorrect values for the XIV=
 notes. (Technically the values were calculated by Janus Henderson Group Pl=
c, which marketed XIV for Credit Suisse, and distributed by Nasdaq, which l=
isted the XIV notes.)=C2=A0From <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/23882452.285958/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvd=
XNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3IwOHNWLjlQMVBKcy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd1ee=
ad34" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the =
appellate court opinion last month</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">For one hour from 4:09 p.m. to 5:09 p.m., the intraday indicative =
value for XIV Notes was not updated every 15 seconds as required and did no=
t reflect an accurate valuation of the notes. Instead, during this hour, th=
e intraday indicative value updated only sporadically and valued the XIV No=
tes at about $24 to $27 per note (the Flatline Value). This published Flatl=
ine Value persisted notwithstanding that, in reality, each note almost imme=
diately was worth between $4.22 and $4.40.=C2=A0It was not until 5:09 p.m. =
(and after more than thirty minutes during which the intraday indicative va=
lue failed to update at all) that NASDAQ disseminated the correct intraday =
indicative value of $4.22. During this hour, investors purchased more than =
$700 million in XIV Notes at inflated secondary market prices based on thei=
r incorrect belief that XIV Notes had weathered the spike in market volatil=
ity without triggering an Acceleration Event.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">While the VIX futures=C2=A0had almost doubled and effective=
ly wiped out the value of XIV, XIV investors didn=E2=80=99t know that yet. =
Their screens told them that the XIV notes were still worth $24+, so they <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23882452.285958/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDItMDkvaW52ZX=
JzZS12b2xhdGlsaXR5LXByb2R1Y3RzLWFsbW9zdC13b3JrZWQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
bf312d8a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
paid $24+ for the notes</a>. It turned out that the notes were worth about =
$4 and they lost most of their money. Oops.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Investors sued Credit Suisse and Janus over this too, and the court tossed=
 that lawsuit out too, and the appellate court did=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>b=
ring it back. Basically it concluded that Credit Suisse and Janus didn=E2=
=80=99t do anything wrong here. The value of XIV =E2=80=94=C2=A0the intrada=
y indicative value that they were supposed to report =E2=80=94=C2=A0was bas=
ed on that=C2=A0<em>index=C2=A0</em>of short-term VIX futures,=C2=A0the S&a=
mp;P 500 VIX Short-Term Futures Index ER. Credit Suisse and Janus did their=
 calculations right, but the=C2=A0<em>index=C2=A0</em>wasn=E2=80=99t update=
d properly after 4 p.m. that day. That=E2=80=99s not their fault; that=E2=
=80=99s the fault of the index provider.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
e index provider is S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices. Apparently XIV investors for=
got to sue S&amp;P, but the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission did not=
; yesterday it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/238=
82452.285958/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS04NA=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc7caf8ec" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">announced a $9 million settlement</a> with S&amp;=
P:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s order find=
s that the S&amp;P 500 VIX Short Term Futures Index ER (Index) published by=
 S&amp;P DJI was intended to calculate values based on real-time prices of =
certain CBOE Volatility Index (VIX) futures contracts. According to the ord=
er, S&amp;P DJI licenses the Index to, among others, issuers that use it to=
 offer securities, including the issuer of the inverse exchange-traded note=
 called XIV, and the license agreement requires S&amp;P DJI=E2=80=99s appro=
val of the description of the index in offering documents. On Monday, Feb. =
5, 2018, the VIX experienced a spike of 115%, but the Index remained static=
 during certain intervals between 4:00 p.m. and 5:08 p.m. that day.=C2=A0Ac=
cording to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, this was due to an undisclosed =E2=80=
=9CAuto Hold=E2=80=9D feature, which is triggered if an index value breache=
s certain thresholds, at which point the immediately prior index value cont=
inues to be reported. The SEC found that XIV=E2=80=99s issuer derived infor=
mation about the Index from S&amp;P DJI=E2=80=99s public disclosures about =
the Index, but the Auto Hold feature had never been publicly disclosed. The=
 SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that S&amp;P DJI personnel did not release the A=
uto Hold for the Index during the referenced intervals, as they had the abi=
lity to do, resulting in the publication and dissemination of stale and sta=
tic Index values, rather than values based on the real-time prices of certa=
in VIX futures contracts. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CInde=
x providers like S&amp;P DJI play a crucial role in the financial markets,=
=E2=80=9D said Daniel Michael, Chief of the SEC Enforcement Division=E2=80=
=99s Complex Financial Instruments Unit. =E2=80=9CWhen index providers lice=
